1A8M | Green Fluorescent Protein (GFP)Biological Role: Originally isolated from the jellyfish Aequorea victoria, GFP absorbs blue to ultraviolet light and emits bright green fluorescence. While its natural role helps the jellyfish bioluminesce, it has revolutionized molecular biology as a universal genetic tag, allowing scientists to watch real-time cellular processes in living organisms.Structural Mechanics: GFP possesses an incredibly stable structure known as a $\beta$-barrel (specifically a 11-stranded "beta-can") that acts as a protective cage. Tucked safely inside this rigid cage is the chromophore, which is spontaneously synthesized from an internal tripeptide sequence ($\text{Ser}^{65}\text{-Tyr}^{66}\text{-Gly}^{67}$). The outer cage shields this sensitive core from being quenched by water or solvent molecules, keeping it highly fluorescent.
